**7. Image disnosing **

  • Noise is common in real world image and
  • it needs to be removed for data cleaning or image cleaning
In[9]:
# importing libraries
from skimage.restoration import denoise_wavelet

# add fake noise
noisy = gray_image + 0.2* np.random.randn(*gray_image.shape)

# denoised the image
denoised = denoise_wavelet(noisy, channel_axis=None, rescale_sigma=True)

# displaying the image
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(12, 4))

axes[0].imshow(gray_image, cmap='gray'); axes[0].set_title("Original"); axes[0].axis('off')
axes[1].imshow(noisy, cmap='gray'); axes[1].set_title("Noisy"); axes[1].axis('off')
axes[2].imshow(denoised, cmap='gray'); axes[2].set_title("Denoised"); axes[2].axis('off')

plt.show()

**8. Segmentation(Labelling the origine **

  • segemnastion helps sepewtareing object fro exapmle cells, arts , region from the background
In[]:
In[10]:
# importing the libraries 
from skimage import filters, measure
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# setting the threshold in the image
threshold = filters.threshold_otsu(gray_image)

# converting to binary image using the threshold
binary = gray_image > threshold

# labeling connected regions in the binary image
labels = measure.label(binary)

# displaying the labeled image
plt.imshow(labels, cmap='nipy_spectral')
plt.title('Segmented Region')
plt.axis('off')  # removes x and y axes
plt.show()

**6. Edge detection with Cany **

  • Detecting edge highlight shape and boundaries
  • This techninq is very use ful in medical imaging and object recognition.
  • why do we call it canny? john F. Canny was the first computer scientist
  • to develop this algorithm for edge detection in 1986. Converting Image to Grayscale (the first btechnic in image process)** Grayscale images reduces compplexstiy and are often the first step in analysis
In[16]:
import cv2
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the image
img = cv2.imread('Lenna.png') # Replace with your image filename

# Convert to grayscale
gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

# Apply Canny edge detection
edges = cv2.Canny(gray, threshold1=100, threshold2=200)

# Display the result
plt.imshow(edges, cmap='gray')
plt.title("Canny Edge Detection for Lenna")
plt.axis("off")
plt.show()
In[]:
face_cascade = cv2.CascadeClassifier(cv2.data.haarcascades + "haarcascade_frontalface_default.xml")

faces = face_cascade.detectMultiScale(gray, scaleFactor=1.1, minNeighbors=5)

for (x, y, w, h) in faces:
    cv2.rectangle(img, (x, y), (x+w, y+h), (0, 255, 0), 2)


plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.title("Lenna Face Detection")
plt.axis("off")
plt.show()
In[]:
import cv2
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the image
img = cv2.imread('Lenna.png') # Replace with your image filename

# Convert to grayscale
gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

# Apply a Gaussian blur filter
blurred = cv2.GaussianBlur(gray, (5, 5), 0)

# Display the original and blurred images
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.imshow(gray, cmap='gray')
plt.title("Original Grayscale")
plt.axis('off')
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.imshow(blurred, cmap='gray')
plt.title("Blurred Image")
plt.axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
